{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01C74KKbCgdZj2LDCG8nDBR2","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\n\n## Review Summary\n\n**Files modified:**\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/worktree-manager.ts` — Added testCommand validation, branch name validation, post-mutex branch re-verification, and catch block IGNORE comment\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/__tests__/worktree-manager.test.ts` — Added 6 new tests (testCommand injection x3, branch name injection x1, branch re-verify after mutex x1, custom testCommand acceptance x1)\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/18-1-merge-serialization-execution.md` — Status changed from `review` to `verifying`\n\n**Test results:** 4889 tests passing, 180 test files, 0 failures\n**Coverage:** 96.71% overall (target: 90%), all 178 files above 80% per-file floor\n**worktree-manager.ts coverage:** 98.41% statements, 92.1% branches, 98.88% lines\n\n---\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Bugs found and fixed:**\n\n- **HIGH — Shell injection via `testCommand` parameter**: `mergeWorktree` accepted an arbitrary string passed directly to `execAsync` (shell execution). Added regex validation: `/^[a-zA-Z0-9_./ -]+$/`. Unsafe characters now cause an early return with `git-error`.\n- **HIGH — Shell injection via malicious branch names**: Branch name from `findBranchForEpic` was interpolated into `git merge --no-ff ${branch}` and `git rebase ${branch}` without validation. A repo with a crafted branch name could inject commands. Added regex validation: `/^[a-zA-Z0-9_./-]+$/`.\n- **MEDIUM — TOCTOU race on branch existence**: Branch was looked up before acquiring the mutex, but could be deleted while waiting. Added a re-verification step inside the mutex to confirm the branch still exists.\n- **MEDIUM — Missing `// IGNORE:` comment on catch block**: The catch block handling merge/rebase failure (line 328) lacked the `// IGNORE:` comment required by the project's boundary enforcement test (`boundaries.test.ts`). This caused the boundary test to fail.\n\n**Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW priority):**\n\n- **LOW — Mutex starvation**: No timeout on `mergeMutex.acquire()`. If a merge holds the mutex for the full 5-minute test timeout, all other merges queue indefinitely. Consider adding an acquisition timeout.\n- **LOW — No logging in merge path**: `mergeWorktree` doesn't log any diagnostic information (which branch it's merging, whether it acquired the mutex, etc.). Makes debugging production issues harder.\n- **LOW — `parseTestOutput` only reads stdout**: Some test runners (particularly when invoked via certain CI wrappers) report results to stderr. The error path extracts `stdout` from the rejection but discards `stderr`.\n\n**Coverage gaps:**\n\n- Branch coverage at 92.1% for `worktree-manager.ts` — the uncovered branches are likely the `testCommand` validation early-return when the regex fails with edge-case inputs, and the branch re-verify path where branch name changes (not just disappears) between lookups.\n- No integration test for actual git merge operations (all tests mock `execSync`/`execAsync`). Real git conflict detection behavior is untested.\n\n**Architecture concerns:**\n\n- The `testCommand` parameter is a raw shell string. A safer design would be an array of arguments passed to `execFile` (no shell interpolation). This would eliminate the injection surface entirely rather than relying on a regex allowlist.\n- The module-level singleton `mergeMutex` means different `WorktreeManager` instances operating on different repos still serialize against each other. If multi-repo support is ever needed, the mutex should be per-repo.\n\n**Items sent back for re-development:**\n\n- None. All HIGH and MEDIUM issues fixed. Tests pass. Coverage passes.\n\n## Token Report\n\n- Total tool calls: 16\n- By tool: Bash: 7, Read: 6, Edit: 3, Grep: 2, Glob: 1, Write: 0, other: 0\n- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): `npm run test:coverage` (~60 lines), `npm run test:coverage` fail run (~60 lines), `npx vitest run worktree-manager` (~10 lines)\n- Files read: 4 unique, 6 total reads (worktree-manager.test.ts read 4 times due to size limits)\n- Redundant operations: Ran `npm run test:coverage` twice (once to fix boundary test failure, once after fix). Could have been one run if the IGNORE comment issue was caught during review before the first run."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a4aa1736266911f50 (use SendMessage with to: 'a4aa1736266911f50' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 61945\ntool_uses: 28\nduration_ms: 258164</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"80ecde4e-3ccc-44de-925d-a2036bf845d1","uuid":"10467f9a-ed99-4a02-b4ba-b1503ac0b6cf","timestamp":"2026-04-03T21:27:17.217Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /bmad-code-review for the story at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/18-1-merge-serialization-execution.md in /Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness — perform adversarial review, fix all HIGH and MEDIUM issues found. After fixing, run `codeharness coverage --min-file 80` and ensure all files pass the per-file floor and the overall 90% target. Update the story status to `verifying` when all issues are fixed and coverage passes. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Bugs found and their severity (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW with brief description)\n- Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW priority items, tech debt)\n- Coverage gaps (files below floor, untested edge cases, areas needing integration tests)\n- Architecture concerns (patterns that don't fit, coupling issues, missing abstractions)\n- Items sent back for re-development (what failed and why)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`\