{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FBKx8VrPEpoFNHZtJPH9Nb","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Session Retrospective — 2026-04-04\n2\t\n3\t**Generated:** 2026-04-04T00:15:00Z\n4\t\n5\t---\n6\t\n7\t## 1. Session Summary\n8\t\n9\t### Stories Attempted This Session\n10\t\n11\t| Story | Phase Reached | Outcome |\n12\t|-------|--------------|---------|\n13\t| 17-1-worktree-manager | done (committed) | Completed prior session, committed as `c5385bf` |\n14\t| 17-2-lane-pool | verifying | create-story, dev-story, code-review all completed; currently in verification |\n15\t\n16\t### Sprint Progress (Cumulative)\n17\t\n18\t- **Total stories:** 64\n19\t- **Done:** 48 (75%)\n20\t- **In progress (verifying):** 1 (17-2-lane-pool)\n21\t- **Backlog:** 15 (epics 17-20 remainder)\n22\t- **Failed:** 0\n23\t- **Epics completed:** 16 of 20\n24\t\n25\t### Session Velocity\n26\t\n27\tThis session processed 2 stories through the pipeline. Story 17-1 was committed from a prior session's work. Story 17-2 completed all three subagent phases (create-story, dev-story, code-review) and is awaiting verification.\n28\t\n29\t---\n30\t\n31\t## 2. Issues Analysis\n32\t\n33\t### Issues from Session Log\n34\t\n35\t**Category: State Regression (1 issue)**\n36\t- Sprint-status.yaml showed 17-1-worktree-manager regressed from `done` to `backlog` despite being committed. Required manual fix.\n37\t- **Root cause:** sprint-status.yaml is a derived view regenerated from sprint-state.json. If the generator runs before sprint-state.json is updated, it overwrites correct status.\n38\t- **Severity:** Medium. Causes confusion but doesn't block execution.\n39\t\n40\t**Category: Design Decisions (2 issues)**\n41\t- AC #5 epic independence ordering uses simplified heuristic (batch parallelism, not sliding-window). Epic 3 won't start until ALL of epics 1+2 finish, even if epic 1 finishes early. Correct per spec but limits throughput.\n42\t- `createWorktree` uses `execSync`, blocking the event loop. Inherited from WorktreeManager design — acceptable for MVP but needs async refactor for production parallel execution.\n43\t\n44\t**Category: Code Quality (2 issues)**\n45\t- Unreachable defensive code: `?? 'Unknown error'` fallback and `activeIndex !== undefined` guard flagged as LOW by code review. Left in place as harmless.\n46\t- No test for pool reuse (calling `startPool` twice). Minor gap — not a regression risk.\n47\t\n48\t**Category: Coverage (1 issue)**\n49\t- 3 MEDIUM coverage gaps found during code review — all fixed. Final coverage: 100% statements, 91.17% branches, 100% functions, 100% lines.\n50\t\n51\t---\n52\t\n53\t## 3. Cost Analysis\n54\t\n55\t### Overall Sprint Cost\n56\t\n57\t| Metric | Value |\n58\t|--------|-------|\n59\t| Total API cost | $329.10 |\n60\t| Total API calls | 2,507 |\n61\t| Average cost per story | $3.40 |\n62\t| Stories processed | 82 (includes retries) |\n63\t\n64\t### Cost by Phase\n65\t\n66\t| Phase | Cost | % | Calls |\n67\t|-------|------|---|-------|\n68\t| verify | $146.44 | 44.5% | 1,198 |\n69\t| orchestrator | $58.82 | 17.9% | 271 |\n70\t| create-story | $36.14 | 11.0% | 315 |\n71\t| dev-story | $33.68 | 10.2% | 300 |\n72\t| code-review | $30.99 | 9.4% | 260 |\n73\t| retro | $23.03 | 7.0% | 163 |\n74\t\n75\t**Key finding:** Verification consumes 44.5% of total cost — nearly half the budget. This is the single biggest optimization target.\n76\t\n77\t### Cost by Token Type\n78\t\n79\t- **Cache reads dominate:** 135M tokens at $202.82 (62% of cost). This is expected — subagents re-read large context windows.\n80\t- **Cache writes:** $72.83 (22%). Each new subagent session primes the cache.\n81\t- **Output tokens:** $53.32 (16%). Relatively efficient — agents aren't over-generating.\n82\t\n83\t### Subagent-Level Token Breakdown (This Session)\n84\t\n85\t| Subagent | Tool Calls | Heaviest Tools | Largest Bash Output |\n86\t|----------|-----------|----------------|---------------------|\n87\t| 17-2 create-story | 14 | Read: 6, Glob: 6 | `ls implementation-artifacts` (~5 lines) |\n88\t| 17-2 dev-story | 20 | Bash: 8, Read: 7 | `npm test` failures (~45 lines) |\n89\t| 17-2 code-review | 17 | Bash: 8, Read: 6 | coverage run (~50 lines) |\n90\t\n91\t**Observations:**\n92\t- create-story ran 3 redundant glob patterns searching for story files. Could be eliminated with a single broader glob.\n93\t- dev-story's largest output was a test failure dump (45 lines) — necessary for debugging, not wasteful.\n94\t- code-review ran coverage 3 times (initial + 2 re-runs after fixes). The iterative fix-rerun cycle is inherent to the review process.\n95\t- No files were read redundantly within any single subagent this session — good discipline.\n96\t\n97\t### Most Expensive Stories (All-Time)\n98\t\n99\tThe \"unknown\" bucket at $50.51 (15.3%) represents orchestrator overhead not attributed to specific stories. Stories 5-1 ($8.84) and 2-1 ($8.51) were the most expensive named stories — both are foundational modules with complex schemas.\n100\t\n101\t---\n102\t\n103\t## 4. What Went Well\n104\t\n105\t- **Zero failures.** 48 stories done, 0 failed. Every story that entered the pipeline completed successfully.\n106\t- **Clean code review cycle.** 17-2-lane-pool had 0 HIGH issues, 3 MEDIUM issues (all fixed), final coverage at 100%/91%/100%/100%.\n107\t- **All 12 ACs tagged test-provable.** The lane-pool story is a pure scheduling module with mocked deps — ideal for automated verification.\n108\t- **Efficient subagent execution.** Total of 51 tool calls across 3 subagent phases for story 17-2 — no wasted iterations, no retries needed.\n109\t- **State management improved.** The sprint-status regression was caught and fixed immediately rather than propagating downstream.\n110\t\n111\t---\n112\t\n113\t## 5. What Went Wrong\n114\t\n115\t- **Sprint-status.yaml state regression.** Story 17-1 was marked `backlog` despite being committed. This is a recurring issue with derived state files getting out of sync with sprint-state.json.\n116\t- **execSync in WorktreeManager.** The blocking call design was flagged by code review but left as-is. For epic 17 (parallel execution), this is a design smell — worktree creation will block the event loop when lanes run in parallel. This will likely surface as a real problem in 17-3 or 18-x.\n117\t- **Verification phase cost.** At 44.5% of total spend, verification is disproportionately expensive. The 1,198 calls suggest verification subagents are doing significant redundant work across stories.\n118\t- **\"unknown\" story bucket.** $50.51 (15.3%) in unattributed costs indicates orchestrator overhead that should be tagged to specific stories for better cost attribution.\n119\t\n120\t---\n121\t\n122\t## 6. Lessons Learned\n123\t\n124\t### Patterns to Repeat\n125\t1. **Test-provable AC tagging.** Marking all ACs as test-provable upfront ensures the verification phase has clear targets. Continue this practice.\n126\t2. **Immediate state regression fixes.** Catching and fixing the sprint-status regression before proceeding prevented downstream confusion.\n127\t3. **Code review driving coverage.** The 3 MEDIUM issues found by code review were all coverage gaps — the review process is working as intended.\n128\t\n129\t### Patterns to Avoid\n130\t1. **Regenerating sprint-status.yaml without checking sprint-state.json freshness.** Add a guard or timestamp check.\n131\t2. **execSync in parallel-execution modules.** Epic 17 is about parallelism — blocking calls are a design contradiction. Flag this in the architecture for async refactor.\n132\t3. **Redundant glob patterns in create-story.** Three similar globs for story files when one broader pattern suffices.\n133\t\n134\t---\n135\t\n136\t## 7. Action Items\n137\t\n138\t| # | Action | Priority | Owner |\n139\t|---|--------|----------|-------|\n140\t| 1 | Complete verification of 17-2-lane-pool | High | harness |\n141\t| 2 | Begin 17-3-run-command-parallel-integration | High | harness |\n142\t| 3 | Investigate verification phase cost — 44.5% of total budget seems excessive. Consider caching verification results or reducing redundant file reads in verify subagents. | Medium | process |\n143\t| 4 | Fix sprint-status.yaml regeneration to check sprint-state.json timestamps before overwriting | Medium | tooling |\n144\t| 5 | Plan async refactor of WorktreeManager.createWorktree (execSync -> spawn/async) before epic 18 | Medium | architecture |\n145\t| 6 | Tag orchestrator costs to specific stories to eliminate the $50.51 \"unknown\" bucket | Low | tooling |\n146\t| 7 | Reduce redundant glob patterns in create-story subagent — use single broad pattern | Low | process |\n147\t\n148\t---\n149\t\n150\t# Session Retrospective — 2026-04-04 (Session 2: Verification & Commit)\n151\t\n152\t**Generated:** 2026-04-04T20:45:00Z\n153\t\n154\t---\n155\t\n156\t## 1. Session Summary\n157\t\n158\t### Stories Attempted This Session\n159\t\n160\t| Story | Entry State | Exit State | Outcome |\n161\t|-------|-----------|------------|---------|\n162\t| 17-2-lane-pool | verifying | done (committed) | Verification passed all 12 ACs. Committed as `66ec8b4`. |\n163\t\n164\t### Session Focus\n165\t\n166\tThis session was exclusively verification and commit for story 17-2-lane-pool. The story had completed create-story, dev-story, and code-review in the prior session. Verification required:\n167\t- Running full test suite (4840 tests passing, 27 lane-pool-specific tests)\n168\t- Confirming 100% statement/function/line coverage, 91.17% branch coverage\n169\t- Fixing proof format to use bash+output blocks (not text evidence) for `codeharness verify`\n170\t- Fixing AGENTS.md to reference `lane-pool.ts`\n171\t- Discovering that sprint-status.yaml is derived and cannot be edited directly\n172\t\n173\t### Sprint Progress (Cumulative)\n174\t\n175\t- **Total stories:** 64\n176\t- **Done:** 49 (76.6%)\n177\t- **In progress:** 0\n178\t- **Backlog:** 15 (epics 17-20 remainder)\n179\t- **Failed:** 0\n180\t- **Epics completed:** 16 of 20\n181\t\n182\t---\n183\t\n184\t## 2. Issues Analysis\n185\t\n186\t### Issues from Session Log (Verification Phase Only)\n187\t\n188\t**Category: Tool/Format Mismatch (1 issue, HIGH impact)**\n189\t- `codeharness verify` expected proof documents with bash command blocks and their raw output, not summarized text evidence. The proof had to be reformatted.\n190\t- **Root cause:** Verification subagent produced evidence in a human-readable format rather than the machine-parseable format the verify tool expects.\n191\t- **Impact:** Required an extra iteration to reformat proofs. This is a recurring cost driver for verification.\n192\t\n193\t**Category: Missing AGENTS.md Entry (1 issue, MEDIUM impact)**\n194\t- `codeharness verify` precondition check failed because `src/lib/AGENTS.md` did not reference `lane-pool.ts`.\n195\t- **Root cause:** The dev-story subagent creates new files but does not update AGENTS.md. This is a manual step that should be automated or enforced.\n196\t- **Impact:** Blocked verification until fixed. Quick fix but adds friction.\n197\t\n198\t**Category: Derived State Confusion (1 issue, LOW impact)**\n199\t- sprint-status.yaml is auto-generated from sprint-state.json. Direct edits are reverted by hooks.\n200\t- **Root cause:** The file lacks a prominent \"DO NOT EDIT\" warning visible to agents. The comment on line 3 is easy to miss.\n201\t- **Impact:** Wasted time on edits that got reverted.\n202\t\n203\t**Category: Pre-existing Noise (1 issue, LOW impact)**\n204\t- BATS integration test BW01 warnings pollute `npm test` output. Pre-existing, not introduced this session.\n205\t\n206\t---\n207\t\n208\t## 3. Cost Analysis\n209\t\n210\t### Updated Sprint Totals (from `codeharness stats`)\n211\t\n212\t| Metric | Previous Session | Current | Delta |\n213\t|--------|-----------------|---------|-------|\n214\t| Total API cost | $329.10 | $334.36 | +$5.26 |\n215\t| Total API calls | 2,507 | 2,543 | +36 |\n216\t| Stories done | 48 | 49 | +1 |\n217\t\n218\t### Session Cost: ~$5.26 for verification + commit of 17-2-lane-pool\n219\t\n220\tThis is notably cheaper than the average story cost ($3.45/story for full pipeline). Verification-only sessions are efficient because create-story, dev-story, and code-review were already paid for in the prior session.\n221\t\n222\t### Cost by Phase (Updated)\n223\t\n224\t| Phase | Calls | Cost | % |\n225\t|-------|-------|------|---|\n226\t| verify | 1,230 | $150.81 | 45.1% |\n227\t| orchestrator | 274 | $59.51 | 17.8% |\n228\t| create-story | 315 | $36.14 | 10.8% |\n229\t| dev-story | 300 | $33.68 | 10.1% |\n230\t| code-review | 260 | $30.99 | 9.3% |\n231\t| retro | 164 | $23.23 | 6.9% |\n232\t\n233\tVerification remains the dominant cost center at 45.1%. The 32 additional verify calls this session (1,198 -> 1,230) added ~$4.37 to verification costs.\n234\t\n235\t### Subagent-Level Token Breakdown (This Session)\n236\t\n237\tOnly the verification subagent ran this session:\n238\t\n239\t| Subagent | Tool Calls | Key Tools | Largest Outputs |\n240\t|----------|-----------|-----------|-----------------|\n241\t| 17-2 verification | 14 | Bash: 10, Read: 3, Write: 1 | `npx vitest run --coverage` (~80 lines), `npm test` (~60 lines) |\n242\t\n243\t**Redundancy identified:**\n244\t- `npm test` ran twice (once for quick check, once for full output capture)\n245\t- Coverage command ran twice (once to verify, once to capture for proof)\n246\t- These re-runs are partly unavoidable (first run for validation, second for proof capture), but a smarter verification agent could combine them\n247\t\n248\t### Cost by Tool (Updated)\n249\t\n250\t| Tool | Calls | Cost | % |\n251\t|------|-------|------|---|\n252\t| Bash | 825 | $93.06 | 27.8% |\n253\t| Read | 561 | $78.42 | 23.5% |\n254\t| Edit | 490 | $61.22 | 18.3% |\n255\t\n256\tBash remains the most expensive tool. The verification phase's heavy use of Bash (10 of 14 calls) for running tests and coverage is the primary driver.\n257\t\n258\t### Story 17-2-lane-pool Total Cost\n259\t\n260\t| Metric | Value |\n261\t|--------|-------|\n262\t| Total cost | $7.58 |\n263\t| Total calls | 61 |\n264\t| Breakdown | create-story: 14, dev-story: 20, code-review: 17, verification: 14 |\n265\t\n266\tAt $7.58, story 17-2 is the 5th most expensive story overall — consistent with its complexity (12 ACs, scheduling logic, full coverage requirement).\n267\t\n268\t---\n269\t\n270\t## 4. What Went Well\n271\t\n272\t- **Clean verification pass.** All 12 ACs verified on the first verification attempt (after proof reformatting). No AC failures.\n273\t- **Low session cost.** $5.26 for completing verification and commit is efficient.\n274\t- **AGENTS.md fix was quick.** The missing entry was identified and fixed without requiring a full re-run.\n275\t- **Sprint-status.yaml lesson learned.** The discovery that it's derived-only prevents future wasted edits.\n276\t- **49 stories done, 0 failures.** The sprint continues with a perfect completion rate.\n277\t\n278\t---\n279\t\n280\t## 5. What Went Wrong\n281\t\n282\t- **Proof format mismatch.** The verification subagent's default evidence format didn't match what `codeharness verify` expects. This required manual intervention to reformat proofs with bash+output blocks.\n283\t- **AGENTS.md not updated by dev-story.** The dev-story subagent created `lane-pool.ts` but didn't add it to `src/lib/AGENTS.md`. This is a systematic gap — every new file needs an AGENTS.md entry.\n284\t- **Verification ran tests/coverage twice.** The verification subagent ran `npm test` and `npx vitest run --coverage` each twice — once to check, once to capture output for proofs. This doubles the Bash cost for verification.\n285\t\n286\t---\n287\t\n288\t## 6. Lessons Learned\n289\t\n290\t### Patterns to Repeat\n291\t1. **Splitting sessions at verification boundaries.** Running verification in a separate session from development is cost-effective and allows human review between phases.\n292\t2. **Checking proof format requirements upfront.** Knowing the expected proof format before generating evidence saves reformatting time.\n293\t\n294\t### Patterns to Avoid\n295\t1. **Assuming AGENTS.md is updated by dev-story.** It isn't. Add a post-dev-story check or make dev-story responsible for AGENTS.md updates.\n296\t2. **Running tests twice in verification.** Capture output on the first run and reuse it for proof generation.\n297\t3. **Editing sprint-status.yaml directly.** Always update sprint-state.json and let the derived view regenerate.\n298\t\n299\t### New Insight: Verification Cost Structure\n300\tThe verification phase's 45.1% cost share breaks down as:\n301\t- ~50% is Bash calls (running tests, coverage, build checks)\n302\t- ~25% is Read calls (reading source files, proof templates, AC lists)\n303\t- ~25% is cache reads (re-reading context from prior phases)\n304\t\n305\tThe most actionable saving is combining test+coverage runs (currently done twice each).\n306\t\n307\t---\n308\t\n309\t## 7. Action Items\n310\t\n311\t| # | Action | Priority | Owner | Status |\n312\t|---|--------|----------|-------|--------|\n313\t| 1 | ~~Complete verification of 17-2-lane-pool~~ | ~~High~~ | ~~harness~~ | DONE (66ec8b4) |\n314\t| 2 | Begin 17-3-run-command-parallel-integration | High | harness | Pending |\n315\t| 3 | Add AGENTS.md update step to dev-story subagent workflow — new files must be registered | High | tooling | New |\n316\t| 4 | Teach verification subagent to use bash+output proof format by default — eliminate reformatting step | High | tooling | New |\n317\t| 5 | Combine test and coverage runs in verification — run once, capture output for both validation and proof | Medium | process | New |\n318\t| 6 | Investigate verification phase cost — 45.1% of total budget | Medium | process | Carried |\n319\t| 7 | Fix sprint-status.yaml regeneration to check sprint-state.json timestamps | Medium | tooling | Carried |\n320\t| 8 | Plan async refactor of WorktreeManager.createWorktree before epic 18 | Medium | architecture | Carried |\n321\t| 9 | Tag orchestrator costs to specific stories to reduce $51.19 \"unknown\" bucket | Low | tooling | Carried |\n322\t| 10 | Reduce redundant glob patterns in create-story subagent | Low | process | Carried |\n323\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_015h16qvaXpY2Uov25AXUvc8","session_id":"80ecde4e-3ccc-44de-925d-a2036bf845d1","uuid":"d546dbad-ff3d-4806-b280-196e92f175f2","timestamp":"2026-04-03T21:37:55.993Z"}
